        "text": "Capital markets are crucial as they enable businesses and governments to access financing. They can make public finances more resilient and flexible, and they can promote financial stability and inclusion.\n\nCapital markets worldwide are undergoing profound changes and will play an increasingly important role in the future, as governments and businesses need financing to address challenges and opportunities such as decarbonisation, ageing populations and technological advancements.\n\nThe integration of ESG factors in investment decisions is an important tool for managing climate and other sustainability risks and meeting society’s growing expectations for a more sustainable economy. Issues exist though around the lack of transparency and comparability of methodologies, and the efficiency of the metrics used in efficiently channelling capital towards ESG and climate goals.\n\nDigital finance is revolutionising how people manage money, make payments and access loans. It is crucial for efficiency, inclusion and innovation. Policies must seek to harness these benefits while mitigating risks for financial stability, investor and consumer protection, and market integrity.\n\nThe OECD monitors the rapid evolution of digital finance, in particular AI in finance, to identify trends and developments and assess how these will interact with the conventional financial system and the implications for financial service providers, consumers and policy makers.\n\nEnabling governments to access liquidity at all times at the lowest possible cost, while considering long-term risks, allows them to better support their economies and citizens. It also aims to enhance credibility, accountability and predictability, thereby contributing to greater market efficiency and lower borrowing costs.\n\nThe OECD provides guidance to public debt managers to help them achieve these objectives, which is more important than ever as fiscal pressures continue to rise against a backdrop of higher overall indebtedness."
